String:
	An object that represents sequence of characters values.
	Immutable -once created, contents can’t change.  
	Able to create string in two ways
		1. Using String Literal
			(*)When you create a string using string literal, it is stored in the String Constant pool memory, 
			   and if another string with the same value exists, it reuses the reference.
			(*)Consume low  Memory space.
		2. Using new keyword
			(*)When you create a string using string object, it is stored in the heap memory and, 
			   will create the new reference.			  	
	A string acts the same as an array of characters.
	Not Thread safe 

String Buffer:
	An object that represents sequence of characters values.
	Mutable -once created, contents can change.  
	Thread-safe
	All public methods are synchronized	& Safe for Multi-threaded environments
	Able to create in new keyword
	Slower than StringBuilder due to synchronization
	
	
String Builder:
	An object that represents sequence of characters values.
	Mutable -once created, contents can change.  
	Not Thread-safe
	All public methods are non- synchronized and not  Safe for Multi-threaded environments
	Able to create in new keyword
	Faster than StringBuffer,String due to synchronization
	All methods used in string buffer able to perform in String builder	